Men of the Nigerian Police yesterday clashed with traders and auto-mechanics at the popular Ikoku Motor Spare Parts market in Port Harcourt, over the sudden death of an auto-technician, Chima Ikwunado in Police custody. Ikwunado and four of apprentices were arrested by men of the Eagle Crack (E-Crack) unit, attached to the Mile One Police division while test-driving two cars they were repairing along Olu-Obasanjo road, and were charged for alleged robbery and cultism. The auto technicians later died as a result of severe torture while his four apprentices, Victor Ogbanna, Osaze Friday, Ifeanyi OsujI and Ifeanyi Onyekwere were charged to Court and are currently remanded at the Port Harcourt Correctional Centre. The traders and auto-technicians had blocked the Olu Obasanjo road and set on fire to protest the killing of their colleagues, who they believed was tortured to death at the Mile One Police division However, midway into the protest, policemen drafted from the Mile One Police division, Iloabuchi Police division and Mile Three Police division, as well as men of the Special Anti-Robbery Squad (SARS) confronted the protesters. LEADERSHIP gathered that attempts by the security operatives to reopen the Olu Obasanjo road was met with resistance by the protesters who pelted stones at the policemen. The development forced the policemen to shot teargas canisters and live bullets into the air to disperse the protesters. The Police Public Relations Officer in the state (PPRO), Nnamdi Omoni insisted that autopsy report showed that the late auto-technician died of high blood level.